---
import '../styles/global.css';
const year = new Date().getFullYear();
---

<html lang="en">
    <head>
        <meta charset="UTF-8" />
        <meta name="viewport" content="width=device-width, initial-scale=1.0" />
        <title>Ivory | Graham Tomori</title>

        <!-- Handwritten Signature Font -->
        <link href="https://fonts.googleapis.com/css2?family=Dancing+Script:wght@500&display=swap" rel="stylesheet" />
    </head>

    <body class="font-sans bg-[#cfc6b8] text-gray-100 flex flex-col min-h-screen overflow-auto">
        <!-- Navbar -->
        <nav class="fixed top-0 left-0 w-full bg-[#3b2f2f] shadow-md z-50">
            <div class="flex justify-between items-center text-white w-full pl-3">
                <div class="flex items-center space-x-3">
                    <img src="/images/stretched-globe-csa-images.png" alt="Globe Logo" class="h-16 w-auto object-contain relative top-0.5" />
                    <div class="flex flex-col justify-center">
                        <span class="text-xl font-bold text-gray-100">Graham Tomori</span>
                        <span class="text-sm italic text-gray-300">Curiosity in Motion</span>
                    </div>
                </div>

                <div class="space-x-6 mr-6">
                    <a href="/" class="hover:text-[#c4b78b]">Home</a>
                    <a href="/about" class="hover:text-[#c4b78b]">About</a>
                    <a href="/projects" class="hover:text-[#c4b78b]">Projects</a>
                    <a href="/Ivory" class="hover:text-[#c4b78b] font-bold">Ivory</a>
                    <a href="/resume" class="hover:text-[#c4b78b]">Resume</a>
                    <a href="/contact" class="hover:text-[#c4b78b]">Contact</a>
                </div>
            </div>
        </nav>

        <!-- Category Tabs Strip -->
        <div class="flex justify-center pt-36 px-6 z-40">
            <div class="bg-white rounded-xl w-full max-w-4xl shadow-sm py-3">
                <div class="flex justify-center space-x-10 text-[#3B2F2F] text-lg font-semibold">
                    <a href="/Ivory/Philosophy" class="hover:underline">Philosophy</a>
                    <a href="/Ivory/Economics" class="hover:underline">Economics</a>
                    <a href="/Ivory/Personal" class="hover:underline">Personal</a>
                    <a href="/Ivory/TBD" class="hover:underline">Highlights</a>
                </div>
            </div>
        </div>

        <!-- IVORY / Main Container -->
        <section class="min-h-screen flex items-start justify-center pt-0.1 px-6 pb-24">
            <div class="bg-white shadow-lg rounded-xl w-full max-w-4xl p-12 leading-relaxed text-[#3B2F2F] mt-6">
                <!-- Header -->
                <h1 class="text-4xl font-serif font-bold mb-6 text-center">Ivory</h1>

                <!-- Intro -->
                <p class="leading-relaxed mb-4">
                    This is the beginning of my journal space. Here I'll be displaying the process of my thinking as I develop my future intellectual
                    frameworks. A lot of this will be based off personal experiences, and academic reasearch, but will be backed up by sufficient arguments and
                    explanations. Everything written here is subject to future change as I grow and develop my individual.
                </p>

                <!-- Signature -->
                <p class="mt-6 text-2xl text-[#3B2F2F]" style="font-family: 'Signature', cursive;">Graham</p>

                <!-- Divider -->
                <hr class="mt-6 mb-10 border-t-2 border-[#3B2F2F]/30" />

                <!-- Highlights Header -->
                <h2 class="text-3xl font-serif font-bold text-center mb-6">Highlights</h2>
                <p class="text-center leading-relaxed mb-6 text-lg">This will be a showcase of my best work under Ivory.</p>

                <p class="text-center text-xl tracking-widest my-6 text-[#3B2F2F]/70">* * * * *</p>

                <!-- SCROLLABLE GOOGLE-DOCS STYLE PAGE -->
                <div
                    class="bg-white shadow-lg rounded-xl mx-auto"
                    style="
                        width: 816px;          
                        height: 1056px;        
                        overflow-y: scroll;
                        padding: 60px;
                        border: 1px solid rgba(0,0,0,0.15);
                     "
                >
                    <p class="text-center leading-relaxed mb-6 text-lg">
                        Highlighted Essay's will go here: Heinz On March 18th, 1969 Cambodia was bombed by a B-52 Stratofortress long range delivery jet.
                        Several 500lb, 750lb, and general purpose explosives were dropped on the Eastern side of Cambodia, specifically the Fishhook region
                        bordering southern Vietnam. Over the next year, ending in 1970, there was a subsequent 3,630 bombings, each wave conveniently codenamed
                        with a mealtime (Breakfast, Lunch, Snack, Supper, Dinner, and lastly, Dessert). After the ‘menu’ bombings ended, another 22,6370 attacks
                        were made by the Americans from airspace ravaging the politically neutral country until August of 1973. At the high end, an estimated
                        150,000 Cambodians died in the attacks, but the number is argued to reach as high as 300,000. Without any attacks on the American
                        soldiers, most Cambodians, with little access to worldwide information, were lost as to the reasoning behind the strikes.
                        ********************** Fifty years prior to the end of the strikes, a Jewish child was born, May 27th 1923. This child was born in
                        Fürth, Germany, just 5 years after the end of world war one, and 16 years before the start of world war two. His birth name was Heinz.
                        In 1934, Adolf Hitler was elected chancellor of Germany. And with his election, the passing of the Law for Restoration of Civil Service
                        came. Heinz’s father was fired from his work as a teacher, and as anti jewish sentiment rose around the country, Heinz was bullied more
                        and more throughout his youth. Teachers would turn blind eyes while he was made fun of, hit, and disallowed from participating in
                        activities with the other children. But none of this compared to the Kristallnacht. On the night of November 9th, 1938, known as the
                        “Night of Broken Glass” to Germans, and Jews alike, a coordination of anti semitic riots perpetrated throughout the country. Heinz’s
                        family synagogue was burnt to the ground. His family was rounded up and violently beaten in their home, having most of their possessions
                        stolen and destroyed. And Jewish businesses were labelled and broke into, then, set on fire, blazing like the modern day west coast
                        wildfires. This was a wake up call for the Jewish community in Germany. Heinz and his family left the country for the United States that
                        same year, just a small amount of time after the Night of Broken Glass. They landed in New York City, moving into Manhattan Heights, a
                        neighborhood along the Hudson river and New Jersey border, slightly west of the New York coast. Heinz was enrolled in George Washington
                        High School on the Harlem river side of NYC, where he was known as a shy, introverted character. At this point he had just turned 15,
                        and was wildly impacted by the Nazi’s reign and the power they had held over him and his family in Deutschland. He was obsessed with
                        history, philosophy, and classical music, some advanced preferences for a 15 year old. He lacked a large social life, since he spent all
                        day working in a shaving brush factory trying to help support his family, attending high school in the evenings and nights after his
                        shifts. In 1943, a fresh high school graduate, Heinz was drafted into the U.S. Army, where he trained at Camp Claiborne, Louisiana.
                        After a year of training, Heinz, who had adopted the Anglican nickname, Henry, was deployed to Belgium just weeks after D-day to help
                        finalize the destruction of the Nazi power and ideology which remained in Europe. He was deployed to serve with the 84th Infantry,
                        travelling through France and Belgium wiping out the Nazis, but was shortly reassigned to a counterintelligence unit in the lower
                        Rhineland due to his intelligence and ability to understand German. At just 21 years old he was put in charge of a small town, Bensheim,
                        about 100 miles away from his childhood home in Fürth. In Bensheim, Henry made sure Nazi officials were properly removed from positions
                        of power and punished for their involvement. For the rest of 1945 and most of 1946, once Bensheim had been stabilized and the war was
                        over, Henry helped identify Schutzstaffel (SS) officers to be tracked down and brought to justice. He was honorably discharged in 1946
                        and returned to NYC for a bit, before moving to Boston to pursue a higher education. In Boston, Henry attended Harvard, studying
                        Political Science from 1947 to 1950, completing his degree in just three years graduating with honors. He stayed in the city, and
                        returned to Harvard the following academic year, graduating again in 1954, earning a PhD in political science, and writing an incredibly
                        well regarded thesis on Peace, Legitimacy, and the Equilibrium. Henry joined the faculty 31 years old continuing at his alma mater
                        immediately after his graduate school, teaching as an instructor from 1954-1957, an associate professor from 1957-1962, then a full
                        professor from 1962-1968, eventually being named director of the Harvard international seminar. While teaching at Harvard Henry was
                        revered highly in the world of foreign affairs, especially in matters regarding Europe. He was a known voice helping advise several
                        councils on actions towards the Cold war threats present. He also wrote several books on the Cold war itself, equilibrium theory
                        politics, and nuclear politics. Then, on November 25th 1968, Henry got an offer to meet fresh president elect Richard Nixon, at the
                        Pierre Hotel in New York City. Nixon talked with Henry for several hours about the current foreign policy situation of the US, and in
                        the end, asked his aid to connect a direct phoneline between the whitehouse and Henry's Boston office. Shortly after, Henry got a call
                        from Nixon. “Hello, Dr. Kissinger? This is Richard Nixon. I wanted to follow up after our meeting in New York. I’ve been thinking, and
                        I’d like you to join my administration.” “Mr. President, I appreciate the offer. May I ask what precisely the role would entail?” “I
                        want you to serve as my National Security Advisor. You’ll be my principal foreign policy advisor. You’ll coordinate the NSC and provide
                        me guidance on Vietnam, China, the Soviets the whole range.” “I see. I must admit, I wasn’t expecting to be asked. You know I supported
                        Governor Rockefeller.” “I understand that. But I also know your scholarship and judgment. I’m willing to take the risk and I think you
                        can do tremendous work here. You’ll have direct access to me and full authority over foreign policy planning.” “I’ll need a few days to
                        consider. It’s a significant commitment.” “Of course. Take the time you need. I’m eager to have you on board. Just let me know as soon
                        as possible.” “Thank you, Mr. President. I will give this careful thought.” A week later in January of 1969, Henry responded. He
                        accepted the invitation to join Nixon’s administration at just 45 years old. Like a young bird leaving its nest to find the true heights
                        it could soar, he made the move to Washington DC and began his daily life engaging with top secret world affairs and President Nixon on
                        a daily basis. Two months later, March 18th of 1969 rolled around. ********************** Henry and Nixon had been planning a secret
                        bombing of South East Cambodia, and the planned date in late March had now rolled around. Very few White House admin members knew, and
                        working with military commanders, they kept the bombings shrouded in secrecy until August 1970, when leaks were shown out by the press.
                        The American public, already wildly against the war, found out about the bombings of a neutral country and were outraged. Not just
                        because of the bombings themselves but also because of the ease with which Nixon and Henry had bypassed the senate's checks and
                        balances. The bombings were justified as necessary to destroy logistical bases and operational passages the Viet Cong and North Viets
                        were using in Cambodia. The secrecy was claimed to be put in place to ensure the bombings wouldn’t be leaked to the North Viet targets,
                        who would simply move their logistics operations outside of the targets in Cambodia. The Nixon administration’s goal of gaining an upper
                        hand in peace talks and greatly reducing the North Viets logistics capabilities was unfortunately, totally unmet. The North Viets
                        ignored the bombings during Paris peace talks in 1970 shrugging them off since in reality the operational centres were easily relocated
                        and barely destroyed after the bombings. With an estimated 150,000 neutral Cambodians killed, and roughly 2,100 enemy troops killed,
                        it’s safe to say, Nixon and Henry’s bombings were savagely misplaced. Throughout the rest of Henry’s years as security advisor he
                        established formal relations with China through Premier Zhou Enlai and Xi Jinping, the latter he continued to meet with up until 2023.
                        He also fostered relationships with the USSR (Russia later), the Middle East, and North Africa. He helped broker peace for both the
                        Vietnam war, and the Yom Kippur War, and left office as a named strategical genius in 1977 at the age of 53. He continued his life until
                        working in consulting, writing, and as a general academic. He wrote several bestselling books on strategy and foreign affairs alongside
                        helping future presidents make heavy decisions in the office. ********************** This Henry we’ve been talking about is none other
                        than the, Henry Kissinger A man with an incredibly debatable legacy, shown from his grassroots. His biggest controversy was the bombing
                        of Cambodia, but was his powerless childhood under Nazi suppression adequate justification for his actions in the Asian country to
                        prevent another power take-over, this time, defending the world against communism?
                    </p>
                </div>

                <!-- Bottom Divider -->
                <hr class="mt-12 mb-4 border-t-2 border-[#3B2F2F]/30" />
            </div>
        </section>

        <!-- Footer -->
        <footer class="bg-[#3b2f2f] text-gray-100 py-6 mt-auto">
            <div class="max-w-6xl mx-auto px-6 text-center">
                &copy; {year} Graham Tomori. All rights reserved.
            </div>
        </footer>
    </body>
</html>
